window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>1>a","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Write a short note on the importance of the presence of an effective transport system in mammals.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The importance of transport system in mammals are:  - Circulate oxygen, carbondioxide, nutrition, hormone, any other metabolites (including enzymes) in the body.  - Homeostasis: maintaining body temperature, pH  - Facilitating immune system","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>1>b","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"State eight functions of blood in mammals.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The functions of blood in mammals are:  - The food we eat are digested and absorb by blood to cell to produce energy which helps in performing various functions.  - Various toxic substances produced by body like ammonia creatinine are eradicated with help of the blood, playing a major role in driving those substances to the kidney.  - The blood transport water and mineral salts.  - The blood contains plasma proteins like albumin, globulin which also bind with various substances helps in transportation.  - Blood transport hormones secreted directly into the blood stream to specific target organ, helping in producing various functions.  - Excess heat from deeply seated organs such as the liver is transported round the body to maintain a constant body temperature.  - Blood (Phogocytes) defend the body against diseases.  - The lymphocytes product antibodies to provide immunity for the body.  - Blood clotting formed by thrombocytes (platelets) during injury prevent excess loss of blood and also prevent entry of germs.","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>1>c","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"List four materials transported in the bodies of flowering plants.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The materials that are transported in the bodies of flowering plants are; water, latex, manufactured food (glucose, amino acids), auxins, dissolved mineral salts, excretory products such as gums, tannins and resins, latex, oxygen and carbondioxide.","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>2>a","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"List four functions of the mammalian skeleton and name a particular part of the skeleton which performs each of these functions.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The function of mammalian skeleton and the particular part of the skeleton performing the functions are:  - The skeleton gives the body shape e.g axial skeleton.  - The skeleton gives support to the body and keeps the internal organs in their proper place. e.g the skull holds the brain, the chest cavity houses the heart and lungs.  - The skeleton helps to aid movement e.g the leg bones come together at the knee to form a hinge joint that enables the knee to bend back and forth.  - The skeleton protect the internal organs from damaging by surrounding them with bone e.g spinal column and rib cage.  - The skeleton provides surface for attachment of muscles e.g vertebra, scapular, ulna and radius.  - The skeleton stores calcium in the bone matrix.  - The skeleton helps in respiration and breathing movements by the rib bones.","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>2>b","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Briefly describe how muscles and bones bring about movement at the elbow.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The process by which the muscle and bones bring about movement at the elbow is describe below:  The biceps and triceps are the muscles of the upper arm on humerus. The muscles work inimically to bring about movement at the elbow. The biceps is attached to the scapula and radium while triceps is attached to the scapula ulna. The biceps contracts while the triceps alleviate to bring about bending of forearm. Triceps contracts and biceps relaxes to cause straightening of the forearm.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>2>c>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"How is support provided for this plant.    Herbaceous plants.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Herbaceous plants: This is through the process of turgidity, which is due to the presence of water in the cells. When the vacuoles of plant cells is filled with water, the cell sap becomes firm to bring turgidity.  In plants, support mechanisms vary depending on their structure and type. Here's how support is provided in herbaceous and woody plants:    Herbaceous Plants:  1. Turgor Pressure: The primary support mechanism in herbaceous plants is turgor pressure, which is the pressure exerted by the cell contents against the cell wall. When cells are full of water, they become turgid, providing rigidity and maintaining the plant's upright position.  2. Collenchyma Cells: These cells have thicker primary walls and are often found in stems and leaves, providing flexibility and mechanical support.  3. Parenchyma Cells: While mainly involved in storage and photosynthesis, these cells also contribute to structural support when they are turgid.","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>2>c>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"How is support provided for this plant.  Woody plants.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"By the xylem with its lignified walls. During secondary growth, extensive wood is formed in the xylem to provide support with the bark as well.  Woody Plants:  1. Secondary Growth: Woody plants have secondary growth, which involves the production of secondary xylem (wood) and secondary phloem. The secondary xylem forms the bulk of the trunk, branches, and roots, providing substantial mechanical support.  2. Lignin: The cells in woody plants are heavily lignified. Lignin is a complex organic polymer that strengthens cell walls, making them rigid and capable of supporting large structures.  3. Vascular Cambium: This is a layer of dividing cells located between the xylem and phloem. It contributes to the thickening of stems and roots, providing additional support as the plant grows.  4. Sclerenchyma cells are integrated into the secondary xylem (wood) and other tissues, providing rigidity and support","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>2>d","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Name one vitamin and one mineral element necessary for healthy development of bones.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The vitamins necessary for healthy bone development are vitamin D and vitamin C while mineral elements are calcium, phosphorus and magnesium.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>3>a","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PROPERTIES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE LIVING CELL","question":"Define enzymes.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Enzymes are biological molecules (organic substances) which are typically proteins that significally speed up the rate of virtually all of the chemical reactions that take place within the cells.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>3>b","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PROPERTIES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE LIVING CELL","question":"State six characteristics of enzymes.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The characteristics of enzymes are:  - They exhibit a reversible action.  - All enzymes are protein.  - Their action is retarded by poison or inhibitors.  - They can be activated by co-enzymes.  - They acts on specific substances.  - Enzymes remain chemically unchanged at the end of the reaction.  - They act best at a specific range of temperature between 35\u00b0C - 40\u00b0C.  - At specific pH, they act best which can either be acidic or alkaline.","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>3>c","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Describe the role of pancreatic juice in the digestion of carbohydrates and proteins in a mammal.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The pancreas produces the pancreatic juice into the duodenum. It provides an alkaline medium for action of the enzyme involved. It contains amylase which converts starch to maltose sugar, trypsin which converts protein to peptide/polypeptides and carbonxypeptidase which converts polypeptides to amino acids.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>3>d>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"In what forms is carbohydrate stored in animals.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Carbohydrate is stored in animals as glycogen or fat.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>3>d>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"In what forms is carbohydrate stored in plants.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Carbonhydrate is stored in plants as starch or sugar.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>3>e","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"e","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : MODES OF NUTRITION","question":"Describe the saprophytic nutrition of Rhizopus.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Rhizopus stolonifer  grows on dead, damp and decaying organic matter such as soil. It secretes digestible juices, that contain enzymes directly on the food. These enzymes cause the food to become soluble, which it is than absorbed by the mold. The mold spreads over the surface of the substrate, sending its hyphae inward to absorb the nutrients.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>4>a>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Define asexual reproduction.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Asexual reproduction is a type of reproduction by which offspring arise from a single organism, and inherit the genes of that parent only and almost never changes the number of chromosomes.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>4>a>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Name two types of asexual reproduction which occur in animals one example in each case.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The types of asexual reproduction with examples are  - Binary fission - Amoeba paramecium  - Fragmentation - Coelentrate  - Budding - Hydra, Obelia  - Parthenogenesis - Aphids, Horney bees","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>4>b","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"In a tabular form outline four differences between sexual and asexual reproduction.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Asexual ReproductionSexual Reproduction1. Involves reproduction through any part of the body. Male and female gametes are absent.Involves fusion of male and female gametes.2. It is a simple process of cell division.The fusion of male and female gametes forms zygote from which develops a new individual. This process is known as fertilisation.3. No mixing of genetic material. Hence, less variation is observed.Mixing of genetic materials takes place. Hence, it show great extent of variation.4. It is a rapid process during favourable conditions.It is a slower process.5. Binary fission in amoeba, budding in hydra.Reproduction in multicellular organisms.","marks":"8","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>4>c","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Make a large, labelled diagram 8 - 10cm long of the human spermatozoon to show its structure.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>4>d","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"State one function each of any three organelles found in the spermatozoon.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The functions of organelles of spermatozoan are;  - Aerosome (head): It contains the nucleus. It also contains enzymes that help the sperm breakthrough the cell membrane of an egg.  - Mitochondria: It produces energy for the cell. Sperm use the energy in the midpiece to move.  - Nuclues: It contains haploid number of chromosomes or DNA.  - Tail (Flagellum): It moves like a propeller around to push the sperm forward.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>a>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Explain the term trait.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A trait is a specific characteristic or feature of an organism that can be inherited or influenced by the environment. Traits can include physical attributes such as eye color, height, and leaf shape in plants, as well as behavioral characteristics. Traits are determined by genes and can vary among individuals within a population","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>a>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Explain the term recessive gene.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"It is a gene whose effects are masked in the presence of a dominant gene.  A recessive gene is a type of gene that can be masked by the presence of a dominant gene. For a recessive trait to be expressed in an organism, the individual must inherit two copies of the recessive allele (one from each parent). If an individual has one dominant and one recessive allele for a trait, the dominant trait will be expressed. Recessive traits are often only observed when the individual is homozygous recessive (carrying two recessive alleles).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>a>iii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"Explain the term test cross.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"This involves the breeding of an individual with a phenotypically recessive individual, in order to determine the zygosity of the offspring phenotypes.  A test cross is a genetic cross used to determine the genotype of an individual showing a dominant phenotype. The individual in question is crossed with a homozygous recessive individual for the trait in question. By analyzing the phenotypes of the offspring, one can infer the genotype of the dominant parent. If any offspring display the recessive phenotype, the dominant parent must be heterozygous. If all offspring display the dominant phenotype, the parent is likely homozygous dominant.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>a>iv","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Explain the term heterozygous.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"This is a genotype consisting of two different or contrasting genes.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>b","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"How do you determine whether a man with blood group 'O' and married to a woman with blood group 'AB' is the father of a child with blood group 'AB' born to them?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Determination of paternity","marks":"7","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>c>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"In rabbit brown hair is dominant over white hair colour. How could you determine that a brown coloured male rabbit is homozygous?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"It can be determined that a brown coloured male rabbit is homozygous by determining its test cross.      It is observed that the next generation (F1 is entirely brown in colour. However, if the members of this generation are allowed to cross-breed (sib-sib matings), then about 25% of the next generation (F2) are white. Hence, the brown coloured rabbit is caused by the dominant allele of the same gene.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>5>c>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"What is the difference between the chromosome number of a gamete and that of the body cell of the same organism?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The difference is that the gametes contain half number of chromosomes (haploid number) found in the body cell (Diploid number).  The main difference between the chromosome number of a gamete and that of a body (somatic) cell in the same organism lies in their ploidy:    1. Gametes (sex cells): These are haploid cells, meaning they contain only one set of chromosomes. In humans, for example, each gamete (sperm or egg) has 23 chromosomes. This is represented as \\(n\\).    2. Body cells (somatic cells): These are diploid cells, meaning they contain two sets of chromosomes, one set inherited from each parent. In humans, each somatic cell has 46 chromosomes, organized into 23 pairs. This is represented as \\(2n\\)","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>6>a>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Write short note on the habitat.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"It is a type of natural environment in which a particular species of organism lives which is characterized by both physical and biological features.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>6>a>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"Write short note on the ecological niche.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"An ecological niche refers to the role and position a species has within its environment, encompassing how it interacts with other organisms and its surroundings. It includes the species' behavior, diet, habitat use, and the conditions it needs for survival. Essentially, the niche describes how a species fits into the ecosystem, including its contributions to the ecosystem's structure and function. It can be considered the species' \"occupation\" within the habitat, highlighting its interactions, resource use, and environmental impact.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>6>b>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"List three instruments used in the measurement of different ecological factors.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The instruments used in the measurements of ecological factors are:  - Light meter  - Metre rule or tape measure  - Hygrometer  - Barometer   - Wind vane  - Rain gauge  - pH meter or pH paper","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>6>b>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Briefly state what each instrument listed in b(i) above is used for.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Light meter: It is used for measuring light intensely.  - Metre rule or tape measure: It is used for measuring distance or length of an object.  - Hygrometer: It is used for determining the relative humidity of the atmosphere.  - Barometer: It is used for measuring atmospheric pressure.  - Wind vane: It is used for measuring direction of the wind.  - Rain gauge: It is used for measuring the amount of rainfall.  - pH meter or pH paper: It is used for measuring pH of the soil, water or a medium.","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>6>c>i","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"Name three plants found in savannah vegetation.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Plants found in the Savannah vegetation are:: vitex, crotalaria, Baobab, Lophina, Mango, Orchid, Silk, Date, Shea butter, Acacia, Date palm, Mosses e.t.c","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Biology>2005>6>c>ii","subject":"Biology","year":"2005","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Name two animals found in savannah vegetation.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Antelope  - Baboon  - Birds  - Zebra  - Cutters  - Giraffe  - Elephant  - Centipede  - Butterfly e.t.c.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"}];